WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.370 --> 00:00:05.916
Prof: "In the
beginning was the word and the

00:00:05.916 --> 00:00:11.178
word was with God"--
somebody actually has memorized

00:00:11.178 --> 00:00:11.670
this.
 

00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:13.720
I'm so proud of you.
 

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:17.440
I got me some good Sunday
school people in the class,

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:21.590
or at least somebody who's done
the reading for the day.

00:00:21.590 --> 00:00:25.290
"And the word was with God
and the word was God.

00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:30.047
He was in the beginning with
God, all things came into being

00:00:30.047 --> 00:00:31.660
through him."
 

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:35.718
God, what a philosophical
sounding term,

00:00:35.718 --> 00:00:37.800
"being."
 

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:42.642
It screams to be capitalized
like Hegel or someone like that

00:00:42.642 --> 00:00:44.120
would do--being.
 

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:48.120
Do you sit around in your dorm
room worried about being?

00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:50.740
What is the nature of being?
 

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:52.770
What is the nature of existence?
 

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:55.590
Yeah?
 

00:00:55.590 --> 00:00:56.950
No?
 

00:00:56.950 --> 00:00:59.960
If you do you're a good
philosopher.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:03.939
"What has come into being--
" now that's also very

00:01:03.939 --> 00:01:06.611
philosophical,
in traditional classical

00:01:06.611 --> 00:01:12.343
philosophy from Plato on,
being is one kind of thing and

00:01:12.343 --> 00:01:16.590
coming into being is something
else.

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:20.355
Things that are truly,
truly, truly being don't come

00:01:20.355 --> 00:01:24.417
into being because that means at
one time they were not,

00:01:24.417 --> 00:01:27.150
and this sounds so
philosophical.

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:30.608
"And the life was the
light was all people,

00:01:30.608 --> 00:01:34.510
the light shines in the
darkness, the darkness did not

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:36.129
overcome it."
 

00:01:36.129 --> 00:01:40.215
You skip down a bit,
verse 14, "The word became

00:01:40.215 --> 00:01:42.379
flesh and lived among us.
 

00:01:42.379 --> 00:01:47.245
And we have seen his glory,
the glory as of a father's only

00:01:47.245 --> 00:01:50.349
son, full of grace and
truth."

00:01:50.349 --> 00:01:55.165
That sounds not only
philosophical but downright

00:01:55.165 --> 00:01:56.599
theological.
 

00:01:56.599 --> 00:01:58.690
"No one has ever seen
God."

00:01:58.690 --> 00:02:01.019
Good theological point, right?
 

00:02:01.019 --> 00:02:06.302
"It is God the only
Son--" have we heard

00:02:06.302 --> 00:02:12.770
anything like that kind of
language so far in this course?

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:18.020
"God the only Son."
 

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:19.750
No, we haven't.
 

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:24.030
That sounds like a Christian
creed.

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:26.680
It doesn't sound like Matthew,
Mark, and Luke.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:30.354
It doesn't sound like Acts,
it doesn't even sound like

00:02:30.354 --> 00:02:30.979
Thomas.
 

00:02:30.979 --> 00:02:34.288
We're in a different world with
this Gospel.

00:02:34.288 --> 00:02:37.669
This is not like anything we've
seen so far.

00:02:37.669 --> 00:02:41.336
So from the very beginning of
the Gospel of John,

00:02:41.336 --> 00:02:45.234
you should know you're in a
different world from the

00:02:45.234 --> 00:02:47.603
synoptic Gospels:
Matthew, Mark,

00:02:47.603 --> 00:02:48.750
and Luke.
 

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:52.050
The style, for example,
over and over again the style

00:02:52.050 --> 00:02:53.128
is repetitious.
 

00:02:53.128 --> 00:02:56.503
There are phrases and words
that come up over and over

00:02:56.503 --> 00:02:59.560
again, darkness and light,
light and darkness.

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:01.199
I already did some of that with
the--

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:03.818
"In the beginning was the
word,

00:03:03.818 --> 00:03:05.960
the word was with God,
the word was God,

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:08.330
he was in the beginning with
God, all things came into being

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:10.620
through him without him not one
thing came into being,

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:12.008
what has come into being."
 

00:03:12.008 --> 00:03:15.445
"Come into being"
is repeated three times,

00:03:15.445 --> 00:03:18.074
a little clue:
don't write your exegesis

00:03:18.074 --> 00:03:19.490
papers like this.
 

00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:22.665
This is not good American
English writing style,

00:03:22.665 --> 00:03:25.842
you're supposed to vary your
terminology, right,

00:03:25.842 --> 00:03:28.479
a little bit,
and alter your terms;

00:03:28.479 --> 00:03:30.060
that's good English writing
style.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:32.111
This of course is actually
fairly good ancient Greek

00:03:32.111 --> 00:03:34.324
writing style which is the
different--the writing styles

00:03:34.324 --> 00:03:35.050
are different.
 

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:38.190
It's also a writing style that
we haven't seen so far.

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:41.483
There's this repetition of
words, there are memorable

00:03:41.483 --> 00:03:45.092
sayings in the Gospel of John
that you don't have in other

00:03:45.092 --> 00:03:45.788
places.
 

00:03:45.788 --> 00:03:49.233
There's a whole lot less action
in the Gospel of John and a

00:03:49.233 --> 00:03:50.538
whole lot more talk.
 

00:03:50.538 --> 00:03:54.330
Just flip open the Gospel of
John almost anyplace and it'll

00:03:54.330 --> 00:03:58.431
start off with a scene,
often a conflict scene with

00:03:58.431 --> 00:04:01.468
Jesus in kind of a--
in conversation with other

00:04:01.468 --> 00:04:01.830
people.
 

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:05.462
But pretty quickly it'll go
into a dialogue in which Jesus

00:04:05.462 --> 00:04:07.688
is saying something,
the other person says

00:04:07.688 --> 00:04:09.210
something, they go back and
forth a bit,

00:04:09.210 --> 00:04:12.860
and then it goes even from a
dialogue into Jesus just being

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:15.818
Chatty Cathy and just talking
for paragraphs.

00:04:15.818 --> 00:04:19.452
We don't have any of this kind
of stuff in the synoptics of

00:04:19.452 --> 00:04:23.209
Jesus just going off on tangents
for paragraphs at a time and

00:04:23.209 --> 00:04:25.839
talking for a whole chapter
sometimes.

00:04:25.839 --> 00:04:29.759
And that's what you get in the
Gospel of John.

00:04:29.759 --> 00:04:32.776
There are some scenes in the
Gospel of John where the

00:04:32.776 --> 00:04:36.081
characters look actually more
lifelike than they do in the

00:04:36.081 --> 00:04:37.300
synoptic Gospels.
 

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:40.586
Have you noticed in the
synoptic Gospels the characters

00:04:40.586 --> 00:04:42.899
sometimes are just a tax
collector,

00:04:42.899 --> 00:04:47.440
a sinner, a Pharisee,
a Syrophoenician woman,

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:50.129
a Centurion who had a slave?
 

00:04:50.129 --> 00:04:53.285
Most of the time they don't
have a name, most of the time

00:04:53.285 --> 00:04:55.540
they'd say one or two things to
Jesus;

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:58.850
one of the longest
conversations with Jesus that we

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:02.689
have with another character is
precisely the Syrophoenician

00:05:02.689 --> 00:05:05.918
woman you've read about,
where, you remember she comes

00:05:05.918 --> 00:05:08.040
and says she wants her daughter
to be healed,

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:10.660
and she's not a Jew,
and so Jesus says,

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:14.783
it's not right to take bread
from the children's mouths and

00:05:14.783 --> 00:05:18.389
throw it to the dogs,
calling her a dog.

00:05:18.389 --> 00:05:22.024
And undeterred she says,
yes, but the dogs get to eat

00:05:22.024 --> 00:05:25.028
the crumbs from under the
master's table.

00:05:25.028 --> 00:05:28.634
That's one of the longest
dialogues that Jesus has with

00:05:28.634 --> 00:05:30.769
another person,
not his disciple,

00:05:30.769 --> 00:05:32.639
in the synoptic Gospels.
 

00:05:32.639 --> 00:05:34.940
Very different when you get to
the Gospel of John.

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:38.490
We have this scene we'll go to
in a minute where Jesus has as

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:40.740
whole chapter talking to
Nicodemus,

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:43.411
we're told who Nicodemus is,
we're told a little bit about

00:05:43.411 --> 00:05:44.619
him,
and then Jesus has a

00:05:44.619 --> 00:05:45.629
conversation with him.
 

00:05:45.629 --> 00:05:49.512
We have a whole scene in which
Jesus is talking to this woman

00:05:49.512 --> 00:05:51.649
at the well, a Samaritan woman.
 

00:05:51.649 --> 00:05:53.646
We know more about this woman
then we know about just about

00:05:53.646 --> 00:05:54.990
anybody else in the synoptic
Gospels.

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:59.057
We know that she's had five
husbands, how many people do we

00:05:59.057 --> 00:06:00.319
know that about?
 

00:06:00.319 --> 00:06:03.206
We know that she's a Samaritan,
we know where she lives,

00:06:03.206 --> 00:06:05.410
we know that she goes out to
draw water.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:09.906
So there are a lot of places in
the Gospel of John where

00:06:09.906 --> 00:06:14.569
characters actually look much
more lifelike and filled out

00:06:14.569 --> 00:06:19.639
than they have been in the
Gospels that we've read so far.

00:06:19.639 --> 00:06:22.310
This lecture is going to focus
on the Gospel of John,

00:06:22.310 --> 00:06:25.653
but as you've already figured
out, one of the main themes of

00:06:25.653 --> 00:06:28.485
the course is how were the
different forms of early

00:06:28.485 --> 00:06:30.980
Christianity different from one
another?

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:33.279
It wasn't just one movement.
 

00:06:33.279 --> 00:06:37.014
It's not like some new religion
just sprang out of the earth or

00:06:37.014 --> 00:06:38.160
fell from heaven.
 

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:40.668
So one of the themes of the
course has been to look at the

00:06:40.668 --> 00:06:41.459
different kinds.
 

00:06:41.459 --> 00:06:43.845
And the Gospel of John and in
the letters of John--I,

00:06:43.845 --> 00:06:46.322
II and III John which we'll
talk about next time--are a

00:06:46.322 --> 00:06:47.699
wonderful example of this.
 

00:06:47.699 --> 00:06:50.350
In fact, if you look at the
syllabus,

00:06:50.350 --> 00:06:54.526
today's lecture constitutes a
certain shift in the syllabus

00:06:54.526 --> 00:06:56.934
because--
although I am talking about a

00:06:56.934 --> 00:06:59.550
Gospel and I have been talking
about Gospels--

00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:03.456
I put a little subheading under
this week that's sort of like

00:07:03.456 --> 00:07:07.362
the spread of Christianity and
how different Christian groups

00:07:07.362 --> 00:07:08.600
look different.
 

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:10.790
We talked about that with the
Book of Acts last time,

00:07:10.790 --> 00:07:13.899
but this time what we're going
to do is we're going to use

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:17.473
Johannine Christianity,
just one of the fancy scholarly

00:07:17.473 --> 00:07:17.959
words.
 

00:07:22.389 --> 00:07:26.910
This refers to different kinds
of John Christianity.

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:29.307
We've got the Gospel of John
and we have three letters of

00:07:29.307 --> 00:07:31.086
John,
and they are similar enough

00:07:31.086 --> 00:07:34.225
although it's quite debatable
whether they're all written by

00:07:34.225 --> 00:07:36.322
the same person,
we'll talk about that when we

00:07:36.322 --> 00:07:37.319
get to the letters of John.
 

00:07:37.319 --> 00:07:40.533
They're similar enough in their
writing style and in their

00:07:40.533 --> 00:07:43.204
terminology,
and in their theological themes

00:07:43.204 --> 00:07:46.209
that we believe that all four of
these documents,

00:07:46.209 --> 00:07:48.541
the Gospel of John,
I, and II, and III John

00:07:48.541 --> 00:07:51.762
represent one form of early
Christianity and we're going to

00:07:51.762 --> 00:07:55.204
call that Johannine Christianity
or somebody might pronounce it

00:07:55.204 --> 00:07:57.839
Johannine Christianity,
it's the same thing;

00:07:57.839 --> 00:07:59.899
so this lecture's going to
focus on that.

00:07:59.899 --> 00:08:02.607
Let's first look at the
narrative differences in the

00:08:02.607 --> 00:08:03.509
Gospel of John.
 

00:08:03.509 --> 00:08:05.350
I hope you noticed this when
you were reading through it.

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:08.321
First, there's this prologue
that I started reading at the

00:08:08.321 --> 00:08:09.990
very beginning of the lecture.
 

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:13.488
It has several major themes
that will occur throughout the

00:08:13.488 --> 00:08:16.560
Gospel, and it's just packed
into this prologue.

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:20.100
There's first Jesus'
pre-existence.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:25.302
In no other Gospel do we get
the idea that Jesus existed

00:08:25.302 --> 00:08:27.100
before his birth.
 

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:30.845
That's counterintuitive to a
lot of us because whether you're

00:08:30.845 --> 00:08:34.529
a Christian or not a Christian
you're used to thinking about

00:08:34.529 --> 00:08:38.524
Jesus as an eternal divine being
who becomes incarnate as a human

00:08:38.524 --> 00:08:40.460
being but always existed.
 

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.962
That's not in the other Gospels
if you noticed,

00:08:42.962 --> 00:08:45.629
but it's definitely here in the
Gospel of John.

00:08:45.629 --> 00:08:48.770
So we get the pre-existence of
Jesus and his divinity,

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:50.549
right there in the prologue.
 

00:08:50.549 --> 00:08:54.461
You get this theme of life;
you get this theme of light and

00:08:54.461 --> 00:08:55.269
darkness.
 

00:08:55.269 --> 00:08:57.519
Jesus comes from light,
he comes into darkness,

00:08:57.519 --> 00:09:00.211
the darkness doesn't receive
him, he brings light to his

00:09:00.211 --> 00:09:02.610
followers, there's the coming
into the world.

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:07.634
The world is not simply the
physical world that you and I

00:09:07.634 --> 00:09:12.389
know, it's the cosmos,
the Greek word where we get the

00:09:12.389 --> 00:09:15.710
word cosmology,
all the universe.

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:20.318
Jesus comes into the cosmos,
so the cosmos as a dark enemy

00:09:20.318 --> 00:09:25.251
place in which Jesus invades it
in a sense is one of the major

00:09:25.251 --> 00:09:30.590
themes of the Gospels that you
get right here in the prologue.

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:34.232
The world is a place of enmity,
the world hates Jesus,

00:09:34.232 --> 00:09:38.427
the world hates the disciples,
the world hates you if you're a

00:09:38.427 --> 00:09:39.940
follower of Jesus.
 

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:42.852
Birth from God,
so there's this idea that

00:09:42.852 --> 00:09:44.820
people are born from God.
 

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:48.504
Son and father linkage,
over and over again,

00:09:48.504 --> 00:09:52.360
God is Jesus' father in the
Gospel of John.

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:55.336
That's true in some of the
other Gospels but it's just much

00:09:55.336 --> 00:09:56.980
more so in the Gospel of John.
 

00:09:56.980 --> 00:10:01.172
John the Baptist as the lesser
of the two is introduced right

00:10:01.172 --> 00:10:02.428
in the prologue.
 

00:10:02.428 --> 00:10:05.019
We don't take a while to get to
John,

00:10:05.019 --> 00:10:07.769
we have John the Baptist right
in verse 6,

00:10:07.769 --> 00:10:10.820
"There was a man sent from
God whose name was John,

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:13.830
he came as a witness to testify
to the light so that all might

00:10:13.830 --> 00:10:14.668
believe in him.
 

00:10:14.668 --> 00:10:16.730
He himself was not the
light."

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:20.232
This guy wants you to know from
the very beginning John the

00:10:20.232 --> 00:10:23.434
Baptist is not Jesus' equal,
he's a secondary witness,

00:10:23.434 --> 00:10:25.548
just so you don't get confused.
 

00:10:25.548 --> 00:10:29.197
There's the idea that "the
law comes from Moses but grace

00:10:29.197 --> 00:10:31.230
and truth come from Jesus."
 

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:34.693
And there is the emphasis on
seeing and knowing as we'll talk

00:10:34.693 --> 00:10:38.389
about later when I hit some of
the major themes of the Gospel;

00:10:38.389 --> 00:10:41.918
seeing and knowing are two
definite themes for the Gospel

00:10:41.918 --> 00:10:45.764
of John and it's all right there
wrapped up in the prologue to

00:10:45.764 --> 00:10:46.710
the Gospel.
 

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:50.190
John is different from anything
else because in this very,

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:53.090
very elaborately constructed
poetic sounding,

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:55.590
almost philosophical sounding
prologue,

00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:58.001
you get lots of the major
themes of the Gospel just laid

00:10:58.001 --> 00:11:00.715
out for you,
so that's a narrative

00:11:00.715 --> 00:11:01.889
difference.
 

00:11:01.889 --> 00:11:05.505
Another major narrative
difference is the relationship

00:11:05.505 --> 00:11:07.690
of Jesus and John the Baptist.
 

00:11:07.690 --> 00:11:12.383
In the synoptic Gospels,
Jesus' ministry does not begin

00:11:12.383 --> 00:11:14.730
until the arrest of John.
 

00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:15.940
Did you notice this?
 

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:19.250
Jesus goes to John the Baptist
to be baptized,

00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:21.850
and it looks like Jesus,
in a sense,

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:24.339
is almost a disciple of John,
although the Gospel writers try

00:11:24.339 --> 00:11:27.288
not to tell it that way,
but Jesus doesn't start his own

00:11:27.288 --> 00:11:30.590
preaching ministry and his own
healing ministry until the

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:32.950
ministry of John the Baptist is
over.

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:35.847
For the synoptic Gospels,
John the Baptist's ministry

00:11:35.847 --> 00:11:38.356
comes here, John the Baptist's
ministry stops,

00:11:38.356 --> 00:11:40.029
Jesus' starts,
very clear.

00:11:40.029 --> 00:11:43.061
In the Gospel of John that's
not the way it is,

00:11:43.061 --> 00:11:45.830
their two ministries overlap
each other.

00:11:45.830 --> 00:11:48.629
So, for example,
sometimes John the Baptist is

00:11:48.629 --> 00:11:52.298
baptizing and the Gospel of John
tells us that Jesus and his

00:11:52.298 --> 00:11:55.595
disciples are baptizing in
another part of the Jordan.

00:11:55.595 --> 00:11:56.279
What?
 

00:11:56.279 --> 00:11:58.779
We don't hear anything like
that in the other Gospels.

00:11:58.779 --> 00:12:01.474
Jesus and his disciples over
here in another part of the

00:12:01.474 --> 00:12:04.364
Jordan baptizing their disciples
while John is baptizing his

00:12:04.364 --> 00:12:05.048
disciples?
 

00:12:05.048 --> 00:12:08.520
And then sometimes John's
disciples leave John and go over

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:10.712
and join Jesus,
and then there's some

00:12:10.712 --> 00:12:12.480
discussions between them.
 

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:15.720
Sometimes John--the
disciples--John the Baptist's

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:19.839
disciples come and ask Jesus'
disciples, what does your master

00:12:19.839 --> 00:12:22.269
do about this,
or this, or that?

00:12:22.269 --> 00:12:25.370
There's an overlap of the two
ministries that you get in the

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:28.840
Gospel of John and you don't get
it at all in the other Gospels.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.100
Another big difference,
Judea and Galilee.

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:35.629
If all you had were the first
three Gospels,

00:12:35.629 --> 00:12:40.043
the ideas you would have was
that Jesus' entire ministry took

