00:16:28.663 --> 00:16:30.048
to come from Bethlehem."
 

00:16:30.048 --> 00:16:32.363
The writer of the Gospel of
John, wouldn't this be a great

00:16:32.363 --> 00:16:34.751
time if he could just say,
oh these stupid Jews,

00:16:34.751 --> 00:16:37.985
they don't know that Jesus
actually was born in Bethlehem

00:16:37.985 --> 00:16:39.950
and therefore he is from Judea.
 

00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:41.320
He doesn't say anything like
that.

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:43.698
He just allows the reader,
you the reader,

00:16:43.698 --> 00:16:47.008
to believe that Jesus really
was from Galilee and you know

00:16:47.008 --> 00:16:48.750
what, that doesn't matter.
 

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:52.722
They must have gotten it wrong,
they must not have thought that

00:16:52.722 --> 00:16:56.440
the Messiah could actually come
from Galilee but he can.

00:16:56.440 --> 00:16:59.586
Again, the Gospel of John
different in its narrative

00:16:59.586 --> 00:17:00.389
structures.
 

00:17:00.389 --> 00:17:03.833
The Last Supper,
the Last Supper in the synoptic

00:17:03.833 --> 00:17:05.960
Gospels is a Passover meal.
 

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:10.029
The Last Supper in John is not
a Passover meal.

00:17:13.078 --> 00:17:16.010
In fact, also,
the Last Supper is not the

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:18.868
institution of the Eucharist in
John.

00:17:18.868 --> 00:17:22.815
In Christian churches we
observe the mass or the

00:17:22.815 --> 00:17:26.219
Eucharist and we say,
Jesus established this in his

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:29.287
Last Supper with his disciples,
"do this in memory of

00:17:29.287 --> 00:17:29.858
me."
 

00:17:29.858 --> 00:17:33.930
That goes back to Matthew,
Mark, and Luke.

00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:35.900
The Gospel of John doesn't have
that.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:38.804
There's no place in the Gospel
of John where Jesus initiates

00:17:38.804 --> 00:17:39.690
the Last Supper.
 

00:17:39.690 --> 00:17:41.608
He doesn't take the cup,
he doesn't take the wine,

00:17:41.608 --> 00:17:42.980
and say, do this in memory of
me.

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:45.358
What happens at the Last Supper
in the Gospel of John?

00:17:45.358 --> 00:17:48.454
He has a foot washing,
there's a foot washing

00:17:48.454 --> 00:17:49.230
ceremony.
 

00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:52.098
Notice again what Christian
tradition has done here.

00:17:52.098 --> 00:17:56.154
Any of you know what Maundy
Thursday means in Christian

00:17:56.154 --> 00:17:56.980
churches?
 

00:17:56.980 --> 00:18:01.440
Maundy Thursday refers to the
Thursday before Good Friday,

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:05.220
which is the Friday before
Easter, and on Good Friday

00:18:05.220 --> 00:18:08.710
according to the tradition Jesus
was executed.

00:18:08.710 --> 00:18:12.032
The Thursday night before is
when he has the Last Supper with

00:18:12.032 --> 00:18:12.920
his disciples.
 

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:16.930
Now in many Christian churches,
on the Thursday before Easter,

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:18.828
not only will they have the
Eucharist service--

00:18:18.828 --> 00:18:21.541
or a communion service,
but they'll also have a foot

00:18:21.541 --> 00:18:22.500
washing service.
 

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:24.480
At the church where I go the
priests,

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:27.317
the different priests will
actually get down on their hands

00:18:27.317 --> 00:18:30.351
and knees and put towels around
themselves and wash the feet of

00:18:30.351 --> 00:18:33.432
anybody in the church who comes
forward on Thursday night before

00:18:33.432 --> 00:18:34.068
Easter.
 

00:18:34.068 --> 00:18:38.250
They're doing that in imitation
of Jesus' foot washing of his

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:40.970
disciples at the Last Supper in
John.

00:18:40.970 --> 00:18:43.830
But notice what we've done
here, again Christians have

00:18:43.830 --> 00:18:47.068
combined the Last Supper and the
Eucharist establishment,

00:18:47.068 --> 00:18:50.715
from the synoptic Gospels,
with the foot washing service

00:18:50.715 --> 00:18:54.430
from the Gospel of John and
they've put them together.

00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:57.288
But they weren't together in
our Bible, they were in two

00:18:57.288 --> 00:18:58.380
separate documents.
 

00:18:58.380 --> 00:19:02.170
The arrest is also very
different in the synoptic

00:19:02.170 --> 00:19:02.960
Gospels.
 

00:19:02.960 --> 00:19:06.076
In the Synoptic Gospels they
come to arrest Jesus and they

00:19:06.076 --> 00:19:08.430
just arrest him and there's a
few things.

00:19:08.430 --> 00:19:10.528
In the Gospel of John there's
this funny,

00:19:10.528 --> 00:19:12.491
funny, funny scene,
it's actually very humorous

00:19:12.491 --> 00:19:14.710
where they come up with the
swords and the clubs,

00:19:14.710 --> 00:19:16.328
it's in the middle of the night
in the garden,

00:19:16.328 --> 00:19:18.618
and they come up to Jesus and
Jesus says,

00:19:18.618 --> 00:19:19.750
who are you looking for,
and they say,

00:19:19.750 --> 00:19:21.144
Jesus of Nazareth,
and Jesus says,

00:19:21.144 --> 00:19:22.502
I am he,
and they all fall over on the

00:19:22.502 --> 00:19:22.750
ground.
 

00:19:22.750 --> 00:19:26.058
It's like an Indiana Jones
thing.

00:19:26.058 --> 00:19:28.527
The power of him saying this
knocks them all over,

00:19:28.527 --> 00:19:31.246
and they get up and do it
again, and they all fall over

00:19:31.246 --> 00:19:31.750
again.
 

00:19:31.750 --> 00:19:34.246
The whole scene of the arrest
of Jesus is very different in

00:19:34.246 --> 00:19:35.150
the Gospel of John.
 

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:38.387
At his trial,
in the Synoptic Gospels,

00:19:38.387 --> 00:19:40.838
Jesus says almost nothing.
 

00:19:40.838 --> 00:19:43.097
Some of the Synoptics say he
said nothing,

00:19:43.097 --> 00:19:45.962
other Synoptics say he said
something, but he's very,

00:19:45.962 --> 00:19:46.788
very quiet.
 

00:19:46.788 --> 00:19:49.830
In the Gospel of John he just
carries on this whole

00:19:49.830 --> 00:19:53.420
philosophical discussion with
Pilate about what is truth.

00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:58.000
He just keeps talking and
talking, very different scene.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.608
On the crucifixion there's some
differences.

00:20:00.608 --> 00:20:03.410
Remember I'm here rehearsing
just narrative differences

00:20:03.410 --> 00:20:05.640
between the first three Gospels
and John.

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:08.634
These are places where just the
story is different in its

00:20:08.634 --> 00:20:09.170
details.
 

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:13.992
According to the first three
Gospels, the crucifixion takes

00:20:13.992 --> 00:20:17.068
place on the first day of
Passover.

00:20:17.068 --> 00:20:20.056
The Thursday night
supper--remember in Jewish

00:20:20.056 --> 00:20:23.210
calendar reckoning,
a day begins at sundown,

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:27.430
so on sundown of Thursday night
that's beginning of Friday,

00:20:27.430 --> 00:20:30.603
and in the Synoptic Gospels
that's the beginning of the

00:20:30.603 --> 00:20:31.250
Passover.
 

00:20:31.250 --> 00:20:34.731
So they wait until sundown and
they have the Passover meal

00:20:34.731 --> 00:20:37.970
Thursday night and that's the
beginning of Friday,

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:40.559
the first day of Passover,
and it's on the Friday the

00:20:40.559 --> 00:20:43.348
first day of Passover that Jesus
is actually executed.

00:20:43.348 --> 00:20:46.338
That's not the way it is in the
Gospel of John.

00:20:46.338 --> 00:20:49.108
Read the execution narrative in
the Gospel of John.

00:20:49.108 --> 00:20:52.953
According to the Gospel of
John, Jesus is not crucified on

00:20:52.953 --> 00:20:57.508
the first day of Passover,
he's crucified on the day

00:20:57.508 --> 00:21:00.630
before Passover,
and how do we know that?

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:04.528
Because it says when they were
crucifying him was the same time

00:21:04.528 --> 00:21:07.608
they were slaughtering the lambs
in the temple.

00:21:07.608 --> 00:21:10.470
Notice, it's a wonderful little
symbolism, right?

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:14.450
Right when Jesus is being
slaughtered, the lambs for the

00:21:14.450 --> 00:21:17.200
Passover meal are being
slaughtered.

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:19.059
Because what you would do of
course if you were a Jew in

00:21:19.059 --> 00:21:22.105
Jerusalem,
you would take your lamb to the

00:21:22.105 --> 00:21:25.441
priest on Thursday,
you'd have them slaughter it,

00:21:25.441 --> 00:21:28.182
pour out the blood,
they'd take a little bit of it,

00:21:28.182 --> 00:21:30.558
then you'd take it back home to
your family,

00:21:30.558 --> 00:21:32.519
or to the hotel where you're
staying,

00:21:32.519 --> 00:21:34.108
or to the picnic ground where
you're staying,

00:21:34.108 --> 00:21:36.564
and you cook your lamb,
and that's where you have the

00:21:36.564 --> 00:21:37.318
Passover meal.
 

00:21:37.318 --> 00:21:40.567
According to the Gospel of
John, Jesus is executed at the

00:21:40.567 --> 00:21:43.410
same time that they're
slaughtering the lambs,

00:21:43.410 --> 00:21:46.237
which means he's not executed
on the day of Passover but the

00:21:46.237 --> 00:21:49.108
day before Passover,
completely different.

00:21:49.108 --> 00:21:52.973
The last big narrative
difference with the Gospel of

00:21:52.973 --> 00:21:57.900
John from the synoptics is this
guy named the beloved disciple.

00:21:57.900 --> 00:22:00.400
Who the hell is the beloved
disciple?

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:02.660
We don't know who he is.
 

00:22:02.660 --> 00:22:07.750
According to Dan Brown and
the--what's that awful book?

00:22:07.750 --> 00:22:10.538
The Da Vinci Code,
right--according to The Da

00:22:10.538 --> 00:22:13.327
Vinci Code the beloved
disciple is actually a girl,

00:22:13.327 --> 00:22:14.308
Mary Magdalene.
 

00:22:14.308 --> 00:22:17.258
I guess it's because he
couldn't believe that Jesus

00:22:17.258 --> 00:22:20.618
could be attracted to a guy,
so he had to invent a girl to

00:22:20.618 --> 00:22:22.269
be the beloved disciple.
 

00:22:22.269 --> 00:22:27.150
Heterosexist as modern
novelists are.

00:22:27.150 --> 00:22:31.394
No, the beloved disciple is a
man and we don't even know who

00:22:31.394 --> 00:22:31.970
he is.
 

00:22:31.970 --> 00:22:34.880
He's Jesus' favorite disciple
in the Gospel of John.

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:39.137
This character doesn't exist in
the other Gospels,

00:22:39.137 --> 00:22:41.048
he's just not there.
 

00:22:41.048 --> 00:22:43.368
Now tradition has said who is
the beloved disciple?

00:22:43.368 --> 00:22:45.842
Well it's the--John,
son of Zebedee,

00:22:45.842 --> 00:22:48.880
younger brother of James,
son of Zebedee.

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:51.291
If you go to the art gallery,
which you will later in the

00:22:51.291 --> 00:22:52.913
semester,
we're all going to take a tour

00:22:52.913 --> 00:22:55.778
of the Yale Art Gallery,
you'll see that when John son

00:22:55.778 --> 00:22:59.595
of Zebedee is depicted in art
he's always the depicted as a

00:22:59.595 --> 00:23:02.516
young man without a beard,
very beautiful,

00:23:02.516 --> 00:23:06.304
almost feminine looking because
he's sort of representing the

00:23:06.304 --> 00:23:07.818
boy that Jesus loved.
 

00:23:07.818 --> 00:23:11.122
Well, we don't know that it was
John, the Gospel of John doesn't

00:23:11.122 --> 00:23:13.429
tell us it was John,
it just tells it was the

00:23:13.429 --> 00:23:14.528
beloved disciple.
 

00:23:14.528 --> 00:23:16.269
Most scholars are just willing
to say,

00:23:16.269 --> 00:23:20.172
whoever this beloved disciple
was, and maybe it was just a

00:23:20.172 --> 00:23:23.868
figment of the literary
pretentions of this writer,

00:23:23.868 --> 00:23:26.221
maybe there was no historical
beloved disciple,

00:23:26.221 --> 00:23:27.038
we don't know.
 

00:23:27.038 --> 00:23:29.902
But he's a strong character in
this Gospel and he doesn't

00:23:29.902 --> 00:23:32.048
appear anyplace else but in this
Gospel.

00:23:32.048 --> 00:23:34.566
Notice in all those ways,
the Gospel of John is very

00:23:34.566 --> 00:23:36.588
different from the other three
Gospels.

00:23:36.588 --> 00:23:41.308
That in itself makes it really
interesting to study.

00:23:41.308 --> 00:23:45.933
It opens up a window for us of
an entirely different kind of

00:23:45.933 --> 00:23:50.558
early Christianity than we would
have if we didn't have this

00:23:50.558 --> 00:23:54.519
Gospel,
so it's really wonderful.

